    "Premium/Discount",
    "premium/discount range",
    "Premium/Discount Range",
    "溢价区/折价区"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A framework dividing any defined price range (e.g., swing high/low, daily range, impulse leg) at its 50% Fibonacci midpoint (equilibrium) into two halves: the upper half (premium) where price is considered overvalued and selling is preferred, and the lower half (discount) where price is considered undervalued and buying is preferred.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a clearly defined price range by marking its swing high (Range High) and swing low (Range Low).",
    "Calculate the 50% Fibonacci level (midpoint/equilibrium) of that range; everything above this midpoint is premium, everything below is discount.",
    "When price is in the upper half (premium) of the range, label it as premium and bias toward sell/short entries.",
    "When price is in the lower half (discount) of the range, label it as discount and bias toward buy/long entries.",
    "The range can be extended or adjusted if price expands beyond the original boundaries, recalculating the midpoint accordingly.",
    "In the discount zone, look for long entries using Fair Value Gap or Order Block; in the premium zone, look for short entries using Fair Value Gap or Order Block."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Premium/Discount framework serves as a confluence for Optimal Trade Entry (OTE): entering in discount for longs or premium for shorts improves risk-to-reward. It is not a standalone signal; combine with PD array structures (Order Block, Fair Value Gap, etc.) for higher probability entries. After a manipulation sweep, wait for price to retrace into the discount (for longs) or premium (for shorts) before entering, with stop beyond the range extreme and targets at opposite side or external liquidity.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering at the opening price or current price after a manipulation sweep instead of waiting for price to retrace into the discount (for longs) or premium (for shorts) within the range.",
    "Failing to adjust (extend) the premium/discount range when price expands beyond the original range boundaries, which can misclassify the current price location.",
    "Confusing the directional meaning of premium and discount (premium should be short, discount should be long).",
    "Using Premium and Discount as an independent entry signal without additional confirmation from PD array structures (Order Block, Fair Value Gap, etc.)."
  ],
